It is possible to lose the device while polling for query status. When D3DGETDATA_FLUSH is specified, this method will return  in response to a lost device. This allows an application to prevent threads from endlessly polling due to a lost device (which cannot respond to the query).An application must never write code that only invokes GetData ( ... , 0 ), expecting that GetData will eventually return  by itself over time. This is true, even if the application has used the FLUSH flag with GetData in the past. For example:	
// Enables an infinite loop:	
while( pQuery->GetData( ... , 0 ) == S_FALSE ) ; // Still enables an infinite loop:	
pQuery->GetData( ... , D3DGETDATA_FLUSH );	
while( pQuery->GetData( ... , 0 ) == S_FALSE ) ; // Does not enable an infinite loop because eventually the command	
// buffer will fill up and that will cause a flush to occur.	
while( pQuery->GetData( ..., 0 ) == S_FALSE ) { pDevice->SetTexture(...); pDevice->Draw(...);	
}


